==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scape
<hw>Scape</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>scapus</ets>
shaft, stem, stalk; cf. Gr. <?/ a staff: cf. F. <ets>scape</ets>. Cf.
<er>Scepter</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A peduncle
rising from the ground or from a subterranean stem, as in the stemless
violets, the bloodroot, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The long basal joint of the
antennae of an insect.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The shaft of a
column.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The apophyge of a shaft.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scape</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scape
<hw>Scape</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scaped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scaping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Aphetic form of
<ets>escape</ets>.]</ety> <def>To escape.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Poetic.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Out of this prison help that we may <qex>scape</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scape</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scape
<hw>Scape</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An escape.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I spake of most disastrous chances, . . .⟦br⟧
Of hairbreadth <qex>scapes</qex> in the imminent, deadly breach.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Means of escape; evasion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Donne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A freak; a slip; a fault; an escapade.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not pardoning so much as the <qex>scapes</qex> of error and
ignorance.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Loose act of vice or lewdness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scapegallows</ent>⟦br⟧
